  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of the legal history of money laundering prohibitions:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Originated from efforts to combat organized crime in the early 20th century\n- Initial focus on preventing criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds\n\n2. United States Developments:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First major legislative effort to track financial transactions\n- Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act (RICO) (1970)\n- Money Laundering Control Act (1986) - Established money laundering as a federal crime\n\n3. International Developments:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)\n- Progressively more comprehensive international anti-money laundering standards\n\n4. Key Legislative Milestones:\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) - Significantly expanded anti-money laundering regulations\n- Enhanced reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Increased penalties and enforcement mechanisms\n\n5. Modern Regulatory Framework:\n- Comprehensive global compliance requirements\n- Advanced technological monitoring systems\n- Increased cooperation between international law enforcement agencies\n\nThis represents a general overview of money laundering prohibition legal history.",
